Based solely on gross observation of the fish, no signs of disease were observed. Parasitized fish harbored cysts on skin, muscles and spleen. On skin, white cysts up to 
2 mm
long were collected from the body flanks of some fish (
Fig. 2A
). Sections revealed that plasmodia developed in the connective tissue of the dermis beneath the underside of scales (
Fig. 2B
). Plasmodia were flattened and surrounded by a thin membrane and an internal endoplasm comprising a loosely defined matrix containing developed spores (
Fig. 2B
).
